24,16,19,8,6]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {The Rubinstein variation
is one of the most popular and solid ways to play against the Nimzo. Nowadays,
it has been established as the main line for white players to pose problems for
us, This is because there is a lot of variety for both sides in these lines.}
O-O {We meet almost all the 4th move alternatives with 0-0. This is the most
flexible as we can choose either to go c5, d5 or even d6 next.} 5. Bd3 {
This is the old main line in the position and remains the most popular
direction. It is a slightly better move order compared to 5.Nf3 as it
maintains some flexibility regarding the knight.} d5 6. Nf3 {This has gone
slightly out of fashion over the last couple of ways as black has many ways to
equalise here. However, we still need to know exactly what we are doing here.}
dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5 8. O-O Nc6 $5 {We maintain the tension in the center. The main
point is to keep the bishop on c1 restricted. We will improve our position a
bit more before releasing the tension. Another big benefit is that there are a
huge amount of options available for white which makes it pretty confusing for
him. We, on the other hand, have a simple plan which we will see soon.} 9. a3 {
The most logical move, forcing us to make a decision regarding the bishop on
b4.} (9. Ne2 {white does not want to get an IQP structure but it is too slow.}
cxd4 10. Nexd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Qxd4 12. Nxd4 Rd8 $11) (9. Qe2 {white removes his
queen from the center and we make the most out of it.} cxd4 10. Rd1 e5 {
We do not want to give the pawn back without a fight.} (10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Nd5
12. Bxd5 exd5 $11) 11. exd4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 exd4 13. Bg5 Bg4 $1 {It's always
nice to provoke our opponent into weakening his kingside.} 14. f3 Bc5 15. Kh1
Re8 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Ne4 Qg6 $36 {With the bishop pair, we are enjoying our
position.}) (9. h3 {white makes a waiting move but it is too slow in the IQP
positions. black has a long-term advantage.} cxd4 10. exd4 {We get a
favourable version of the IQP due to the unnecessary move h3.} b6 {b7 is the
best square for the bishop along the long diagonal. d5 square is the key for
both sides.} 11. Re1 Bb7 12. Bg5 (12. d5 {does not work due to} Na5 $17) 12...
h6 13. Bh4 Rc8 14. Bd3 Be7 $11 {We are ready to go Nb4 next and get full
control over the d5 square.}) (9. Re1 {This does not make much sense when we
have not taken on d4 yet.} h6 {We make a useful waiting move, stopping a future
