O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nge2 {This has fallen out of fashion over the last few years
and for good reason. The knight is much better on f3 in the IQP positions.
Forcing us to give up the bishop on c3 also wastes a lot of time.} dxc4 7. Bxc4
c5 {We play the same way as in the main lines. However, we will not hesitate
to take on d4 at the first opportunity here.} 8. a3 {white forces us to take on
c3 here.} (8. O-O cxd4 {At the first chance we take on d4, going for an IQP
position,} 9. exd4 {The only move to try and pose any problems for us. The
major difference compared to the Karpov variation (with the knight on f3) is
that the knight is more passive on e2. It cannot jump to e5 easily. Of course,
there are a few advantages to the knight on e2 as we will see.} (9. Qxd4 Nc6
10. Qh4 Be7 $11 {[%cal Gd8b6]}) (9. Nxd4 {white just wants to equalise here.}
Bd7 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 10. Qb3 {Happened in 0-1 (20) Ding, J (1904) -Gukesh, D (
2563) Lichess.org INT 2020. He should have continued with} Qe7 11. a3 Bxc3 12.
Qxc3 e5 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ga8c8] Our lead in development compensates for the
bishop pair.}) 9... Nc6 10. a3 {white again tries to force us to take on c3.} (
10. Bf4 Bd6 $11 {We are happy to trade minor pieces.}) (10. Qd3 Bd6 {We create
a threat of Na5 or Nb4. The bishop is more active here compared to e7.} 11. a3
h6 $11 {We can continue with Bd7 next followed by Ne7.}) (10. Be3 h6 {This is
a useful move to cover g5 and next we can go for the move Ne7.} (10... Ne7 {
is also good} 11. Bg5 Nf5 $11) 11. Ng3 Ne7 {We will easily take over the
position if given a couple of moves.} 12. Qf3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Qc7 $11 {[%csl Rc3,
Rc4][%cal Ge7d5,Gb7b6,Gc8b7]}) (10. Bg5 {This does not achieve as much as in
the Nf3 lines.} h6 {I always like to immediately clarify white's intentions.}
11. Bxf6 (11. Bh4 Be7 {We will go Qb6 next followed by Rd8 putting pressure on
the d4 pawn.} 12. a3 Qb6 $36 {[%cal Gf8d8]}) 11... Qxf6 12. d5 Ne5 13. Bb3 Bd7
{We want to bring the rook to d8. We let white capture on e6.} (13... Qh4 14.
g3 Qg4 15. a3 Nf3+ 16. Kg2 Nh4+ 17. Kg1 {1/2-1/2 (70) Babychuk,V (2200)
-Voveris,G (2352) ICCF email 2017}) 14. dxe6 Bxe6 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. Qxd5 Nc6 $11
{The position is around equal although it looks like white has some issues
with the b2 pawn.}) 10... Bd6 $1 {We retreat to a pretty active square and the
bonus is that Bg5 is not possible tactically.} (10... Bxc3 {is also possible}
11. bxc3 b6 $11) 11. h3 (11. Bg5 $2 Bxh2+ $17) (11. Qd3 h6 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13.
Qxe4 Ne7 14. Bd3 f5 15. Qf3 Ng6 $11) (11. Ba2 h6 {We can always go for the move
h6 before Ne7 to be sure. I have generally tried to avoid it if possible but
here with the bishop still on c1 it is a serious idea.} 12. Qd3 Ne7 13. Rd1 Bd7
$11 {[%cal Gd7c6]}) 11... h6 {Again with the bishop on c1, I feel more
comfortable going for h6 before Ne7.} 12. Be3 Ne7 13. Bd3 (13. Qd3 Bd7 14. Rad1
{1/2-1/2 (55) Short, N (2684) -Vaibhav, S (2527) Jakarta 2013} Bc6 $15) 13...
Bd7 {We will get the bishop to c6 and get full control over d5. Even a trade on
c6 is usually good for us as it opens up the 'b' file.} (13... b6 $11) 14. Ne4
Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Rc8 $11) 8... Bxc3+ (8... Ba5 9. dxc5 $14) 9. Nxc3 {We were not
able to maintain the tension with Ba5 as in the main line. However, the moves
