{[%evp 0,38,27,27,28,21,26,30,17,23,24,28,32,32,20,17,38,25,49,33,64,41,74,67,
109,30,31,22,26,15,29,24,50,54,54,57,62,53,38,32,52]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. e3 (4. Bd2 {Is another move order to reach the starting position for
this variation. We will briefly take a look at the independent options here.}
O-O 5. a3 (5. Nf3 d5 6. e3 {transposes.}) 5... Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Ne4 {We will end
up winning the bishop back very quickly. In most cases, the move a4 is pretty
slow and gives us the chance to fight for the center.} 7. Qc2 (7. Rc1 d6 $1 {
After winning the dark-squared bishop I really like the plan of going for the
e5 plan.} 8. Nf3 Nxc3 9. Rxc3 Nd7 10. e4 e5 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gd8e7] We have
the better bishop and very good practical chances to outplay our opponent.}) (
7. Bb4 {is not good due to} c5 8. dxc5 a5 9. Bd2 a4 $15 {We have managed to
fix the structure on the queenside in our favour.}) 7... Nxc3 8. Qxc3 {This is
similar to the 4.Qc2 variation with the exchange of dark-squared bishops which
should definitely favour us.} b6 9. Nf3 Bb7 10. e3 d6 {Both here and in the Qc2
lines I like the plan of going for the move e5 or c5. We keep the diagonal
open for our bishop on b7.} 11. Be2 Nd7 12. O-O c5 13. Rad1 Qc7 $11) 4... O-O
5. Bd2 {This has become a major trend over the last few years. The main
attraction is that black does not have too many viable options early on. The
play remains consistent for white. The drawback however is that the bishop is
not that active on d2.} d5 6. Nf3 (6. Bd3 {allows us to go} dxc4 {In the Bd2
system, it is rarely a great idea for white to waste a tempo with Bd3-c4.} 7.
Bxc4 c5 8. a3 (8. Nf3 cxd4 $11) 8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Ne4 $11 10. Ne2 Nxc3 11. bxc3
Qc7 {This is a good pawn structure for us and we will continue with b6 and Bb7.
}) (6. Rc1 {Not sure what white is trying to achieve by delaying Nf3 but it
allows us to go for the direct-} c5 $1 {We make use of the fact that the
knight is still on g1 and we want to take on d4 next.} 7. Nf3 (7. a3 Bxc3 8.
Bxc3 cxd4 9. Bxd4 Nc6 10. Bc3 Qe7 $11 {[%cal Gf8d8] We will be going for the
move e5 soon and we are ahead in development. It compensates for the bishop
pair.}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 (8. Nxd4 e5 $36) 8... Nc6 9. a3 Bxc3 (9... Be7 $11 {
[%cal Ge6e5,Gc4c5]}) 10. Bxc3 {white has delayed his development a lot to win
the dark-squared bishop.} dxc4 {This is the most ambitious way to go for an IQP
position. The downside is that we allow the bishop to come to c4 in one go.} (
10... Ne4 $11) 11. Bxc4 b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Qd3 Ne7 14. Rfe1 Rc8 $11 {We will go
Nfd5 next and maybe bring the other knight to f5/g6. It feels easier to play
as black due to his control over d5.}) (6. a3 {This is a non-developing move
so early from white. It usually makes sense to go a3 only when we are forced
to take on c3.} Be7 {We get a great version of the QGD with white's bishop on
d2.} 7. Nf3 b6 {We play in the spirit of the Tartakower variation in the QGD.
This is our standard plan in these positions.} (7... c5 $5) 8. cxd5 exd5 {
We get similar positions in our main lines with the rook on c1 instead of a3
which is a much better inclusion.} 9. Bd3 (9. b4 c5 10. bxc5 bxc5 $11) (9. Rc1
c5 {We always go for the move c5 before developing our b8 knight to keep the
options open.} 10. dxc5 (10. Ne5 Bb7 11. Bd3 Nbd7 12. O-O Ne4 $1 $11 {We want
to take on e5 next. It is not going to be easy to dislodge the knight on e4.})
10... bxc5 11. Bd3 {Happened in the game 1-0 (49) Ding, L (2806)
-Praggnanandhaa, R (2642) chess24.com INT 2022. black was more comfortable
after} Nc6 12. O-O Rb8 $15) 9... c5 10. O-O Bb7 11. Ne5 Nc6 $1 {Here we want
to put pressure on the d4 pawn.} (11... Nbd7 12. f4 Ne4 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Bb5
$14) 12. Rc1 Bd6 {We are trying to force him to go for the move f4 which would
severely weaken the e4 square.} 13. Ng4 Ne8 $1 $11 {A typical but nice idea
preparing the move f5. The knight on g4 is not so well placed. We will see
something similar in the main lines.}) 6... b6 {We maintain the tension in the
center and develop our bishop to b7. We will always meet Be2/d3 with dxc4
gaining a tempo. The move b6 also helps us go for the c5 break in the future.}
7. cxd5 {The general rule in QGD type of positions is to take on d5 whenever
black goes for the move b6. If white releases the tension earlier we will
usually get our bishop to f5/g4. He does have to release the tension at some
point to develop his f1 bishop.} (7. a3 Be7 {transposes}) (7. Rc1 Bb7 8. cxd5
exd5 {transposes}) (7. Bd3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {We can either
directly go for the move c5 next or get our bishop back to d6/e7 first. Both
work well for us as white has played too slowly so far.} 10. Qe2 (10. Rc1 {
We have a lot of time here since e4 is not a threat yet.} Bd6 11. Qe2 a6 $5 {
We are very ambitious and want to get both b5 and c5.} 12. e4 b5 13. Bd3 c5 14.
e5 Bxf3 15. gxf3 cxd4 $11 {The position is dynamically balanced with our
better structure compensated by the bishop pair.}) 10... c5 (10... Bd6 $11) 11.
Rfd1 (11. a3 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Ne4 $11) 11... cxd4 12. exd4 (12. Nxd4 a6 13. Be1 b5
$36) 12... Rc8 13. Bd3 h6 {Has been played only twice. It is a natural move
stopping Bg5 and we can continue with Qe7 next.} (13... Bxc3 {is the most
played move.}) 14. Rac1 Qe7 15. a3 Bxc3 16. bxc3 (16. Bxc3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nd5
18. Bd2 Rfd8 $11 {Our control over the center neutralises the bishop pair.})
16... Qd6 17. a4 Rfd8 18. h3 Nc5 $1 $11 {[%cal Gc5e4] We get our knight to e4.
Our pieces are pretty active while white is unable to mobilise his pieces.})
7... exd5 {There are several options here. Our plan remains very consistent.
We want to get our bishop back and go for the move c5 quickly. We should be
ready to deal with the Ne5 plan. If given the option we would like to get our
bishop to d6.} 8. Bd3 {This is the most played move in the position. white
looks to complete his development but he gives us the chance to get our bishop
to d6 comfortably.} (8. Ne5 {Will likely transpose back to one of the other
variations.} Bd6 9. Bd3 (9. Nb5 {is not good here due to} Bxe5 10. dxe5 Ne4 $15
) 9... c5 10. Nb5 (10. O-O Bb7 {transposes.}) 10... Be7 11. O-O Bb7 $11 {
We can now go a6 followed by c4 and b5. We end up gaining a few tempi on the
queenside.}) (8. Be2 Bd6 $1 {We immediately take the chance to bring the
bishop back to d6 before white can try Rc1 and Nb5 ideas.} 9. Ne5 {is too
early here} c5 10. O-O Bb7 11. Rc1 Nc6 $11 {white has to give up control over
the center.}) (8. Qc2 {white is ready to meet Bd6 with Nb5. However, the queen
is usually not well placed on c2 in these positions.} Re8 $1 {We want to get
our bishop directly to f8 followed by c5 and Nc6.} 9. Bd3 Bf8 10. O-O c5 $11)
8... Bd6 $1 {We have seen this idea before- we immediately bring the bishop
back, not allowing Rc1 and Nb5 ideas.} 9. O-O (9. Rc1 c5 $11) (9. Ne5 c5 10.
O-O Bb7 11. f4 Nc6 12. Ne2 cxd4 13. exd4 Ne4 $11) 9... Re8 $1 {We stop both e4
and Ne5 ideas. We maintain the option of going for the move Ba6 anytime.} (9...
c5 10. e4 $1 $16) 10. Nb5 {white kicks the knight back to get the e5 square
for the knight.} (10. Qc2 {I faced this in a classical game last year. It is
logical to control e4 but it will come under a lot of fire along the 'c' file.
Moreover, Nc6 now comes with a tempo.} c5 $1 11. e4 {white tries to open up the
center.} (11. dxc5 bxc5 {This hanging pawns structure is great for us and the
bishop on d2 is useless.}) 11... c4 12. e5 (12. Be2 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 $6 {Happened
in the game 0-1 (78) Raahul, V (2478) -Arjun,K (2506) Gurugram 2022. I could
have got an edge after} Bf5 $15) 12... cxd3 13. Qxd3 Bb4 14. exf6 Ba6 15. Nb5
Bxd2 16. Nxd2 Qxf6 {black is very comfortable here with Nc6 to follow.}) (10.
Re1 Bb7 {We keep control over e4.} 11. Qc2 Na6 $1 {[%cal Ga6b4] We kind of
gain a tempo by threatening to go Nb4. The knight will eventually come to e6
via c7.} 12. a3 c5 13. e4 {white tries to blast open the center but we do have
enough pieces to fight back.} (13. dxc5 bxc5 $11) 13... cxd4 14. Nxd5 Nc5 15.
Bg5 Rc8 $11 {The position is dynamically balanced here. We are threatening to
go for the move Ne4 next.}) (10. Rc1 c5 {We have got everything that we wanted
in time. white has to be careful now as we can very easily take over the
initiative. The dangerous plan of Ne5 has been stopped.} 11. Bb5 (11. dxc5 {
Should be a good sign for us with the bishop on d2.} bxc5 12. Qa4 a6 13. Rfd1
Nbd7 $11) (11. Nb5 {A desperate attempt to get the knight to e5.} Bf8 12. Ne5
Bb7 13. f4 $6 {This is too weakening for white as he is unable to maintain
good control over d4.} (13. a4 a6 14. Nc3 Nc6 $36) 13... Nc6 {If white gets a
couple of tempi we would be toast but as it is he is unable to defend d4.} (
13... Ba6 14. a4 Bb7 15. Be1 {was great for white in the game 1/2-1/2 (79)
Kovalenko, I (2663) -Neiksans, A (2552) Riga 2019}) 14. Be1 a6 15. Nc3 cxd4 16.
Nxc6 {This is a huge concession.} Bxc6 17. exd4 Ne4 $17) 11... Bd7 {white is
trying to misplace the bishop to d7 but it does not help much.} 12. b3 h6 {
We will keep maintaining the tension. We can always go for the move Nc6.} (
12... a6 13. Bxd7 Nbxd7 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Ne2 $14 {1/2-1/2 (34) Anton Guijarro,
D (2675) -Giri,A (2764) chess24.com INT 2020:}) 13. h3 Nc6 14. Re1 cxd4 15.
exd4 Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 a6 $11) 10... Bf8 11. Ne5 Ba6 {This is the benefit of our
move order. The exchange of light-squared bishop is in our favour.} 12. Be1 (
12. Rc1 c5 {[%cal Gc5c4]} 13. a4 Bb7 $11 {We will go a6 next followed by Nc6.
The inclusion of a4 and a6 should definitely be in our favour.}) 12... c6 13.
Nc3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Qc8 {The queen will be well placed on b7 to play on the
queenside. The knight will go to d7.} 15. Rc1 Qb7 16. f4 Nbd7 17. Bh4 {All
this happened in the game 0-1 (62) Prohaszka, P (2585) -Praggnanandhaa, R (2690
) Budapest 2023. Even better here was} b5 18. Bxf6 Nxf6 19. Rc2 Nd7 $11 {
We prepare to go f6 next.} *

