{[%evp 0,32,28,28,28,26,24,24,23,28,26,18,24,18,18,19,38,29,17,30,43,22,58,43,
110,76,102,39,74,35,51,25,11,16,16]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5.
Bd2 d5 6. Nf3 b6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Rc1 {I believe that this is the best move
order for white as it stops the plan of going directly to d6. However, it is
not a proper developing move and we can make use of the time lost.} c5 $1 {
We want to get the pawn to c4 quickly. This is a very rare move (5th most
popular) but it has been played by a few strong players. I like the fact that
some of the most played moves here actually lead to a slight edge for us.} 9.
Be2 {This is the best square for the bishop here.} (9. Bd3 $6 {Invites us to go
c4 which was our plan anyway.} c4 10. Bb1 Bxc3 $1 $146 {This makes a lot of
sense here as we will play differently depending on how white recaptures.} 11.
Bxc3 {This looks more active preparing to go Ne5 next but we stop it with-} (
11. bxc3 Nc6 12. O-O Re8 $15 {We can continue with Bg4 and b5 next. white
lacks any counterplay.}) 11... Bg4 $1 {We will either take on f3 or force
white to make weakness on the kingside (with h3,g4) .} 12. h3 (12. O-O b5 $15)
12... Bh5 13. b3 b5 14. bxc4 bxc4 15. Qa4 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Qc8 $15 {We will go
Nc6-e7 next. With the center closed the bishops lack good diagonals.}) (9. a3 {
Looks natural but is an inaccuracy as it allows us to get quick play on the
queenside.} Bxc3 10. Bxc3 c4 $1 {We close down the center and will get our
knight to the juicy e4 square soon. Another plan is to b5, a5 and b4.} 11. b3 (
11. Nd2 {is pretty slow.} b5 12. Be2 Nc6 13. b3 Re8 14. O-O Bf5 15. Re1 Qd6 16.
bxc4 bxc4 17. Ra1 Rab8 $17 {1/2-1/2 (70) Navara,D (2684) -Santos Latasa,J (2668
) Katowice 2022}) (11. Be2 b5 12. O-O Be6 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6] Here we will try
to go Nc6, a5 and b4.}) (11. Ne5 Ne4 12. Be2 Nxc3 {Again we take on c3 as we
want white to decide how to recapture.} 13. bxc3 (13. Rxc3 b5 $15) 13... Qe7
14. Ra1 Nd7 15. Nxd7 Bxd7 $15) 11... b5 12. bxc4 bxc4 (12... dxc4 $5 $15) 13.
Be2 Ne4 14. O-O Bg4 {We would like to trade the light-squared bishops and play
against the bishop on c3.} 15. h3 Bh5 $15 {0-1 (52) Colovic,A (2449) -Hracek,Z
(2578) Skopje 2019}) (9. dxc5 {This is a small concession here with the bishop
on d2. The hanging pawns have great dynamic potential.} bxc5 10. Na4 (10. Bb5 {
I do not understand the point of promoting a6 or getting the bishop to a4.} a6
11. Ba4 (11. Bd3 c4 12. Bb1 Bg4 13. Ne2 {0-1 (53) Aczel,G (2474) -Parkhov,Y (
2479) Budapest 2022} a5) 11... d4 $1 12. exd4 cxd4 13. Ne2 Bxd2+ 14. Qxd2 d3
15. Ned4 Qe7+ 16. Kf1 Bd7 $11 {We have excellent compensation with the king on
f1.}) 10... Bxd2+ 11. Nxd2 d4 $1 {We want to play as energetically as possible
having a big lead in development.} 12. Be2 dxe3 13. fxe3 Nbd7 $11 {1-0 (63)
Erigaisi,A (2626) -Gukesh, D (2599) Plovdiv 2021}) 9... c4 $1 {This is quite a
commital decision but we believe in our play on the queenside. We will soon
take on c3 and go for b5-b4.} 10. O-O (10. b3 Bxc3 $1 {We give up our bishop
to get the move b5 and maintain our grip on the queenside.} 11. Bxc3 b5 12.
bxc4 bxc4 13. Nd2 {Happened in the game 0-1 (47) Bluebaum, M (2672) -Lazavik, D
(2553) Chess.com INT 2023. We are already taking over the initiative after-}
Bf5 14. f3 (14. O-O Re8 $15 {[%csl Re3]}) 14... Nbd7 15. O-O Nb6 $11 {[%csl
Ge3][%cal Gf8e8]}) 10... a6 $1 {Now we prepare b5 without having to take on c3.
} 11. Ne5 (11. a3 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 {In the game 0-1 (53) Sandipan,C (2475)
-Panesar, V (2387) New Delhi 2023 black could have taken over after} (12. bxc3
Qe7 $17) 12... b5 $15 {[%cal Gf6e4]}) (11. a4 Nc6 12. b3 Bxc3 {We take on c3
whenever white tries to break our structure on the queenside.} 13. Bxc3 b5 14.
Ne5 {Happened in 1/2-1/2 (65) Aditya,M (2459) -Sethuraman,S (2620)
Castelldefels 2021.} Qb6 {A nice prophylactic move aimed against the move f3.}
15. f3 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qxe3+ 17. Kh1 Nh5 $132) 11... b5 12. a4 Qb6 {We want to go
Nc6 and Be6 next. We always have the option of taking on c3 and advancing our
pawns.} (12... Qd6 $5 {is another option} 13. axb5 (13. Ra1 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Nc6
$11) 13... Bxc3 14. bxc3 axb5 $11) 13. Ra1 $146 {This is a very hard move to
play.} (13. Qc2 {This was played by my teammate in the Chess Super League- 0-1
(34) Gupta, A (2628) -Giri, A (2774) Chess.com INT 2021.} Bxc3 14. bxc3 Nc6 15.
Nxc6 Qxc6 $15 {We can start playing on the kingside too with h5 and g6. You
can check out the full game.}) 13... Bb7 14. Qc2 Bxc3 15. bxc3 (15. Bxc3 b4 $17
) 15... Nc6 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 $11 {We will soon regroup our pieces to the kingside,
The queenside is under control.} *


