{[%evp 0,40,28,28,24,26,27,22,23,23,18,18,18,11,10,8,19,30,15,9,21,40,21,21,7,
4,-2,-45,-45,-12,-3,0,0,0,0,8,15,9,9,5,5,7,1]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
e3 O-O 5. Nf3 {This is supposed to be a less precise move order compared to 5.
Bd3 as it gives black more options. We will be happy to transpose back to the
Karpov variation but we will look at some independent options for white here.}
(5. Qc2 {A weird mix between two different systems.} d5 (5... c5 $5) 6. a3 (6.
Bd3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5 $11 {We get a much better version of the usual lines as
the queen is not doing much on c2.}) (6. Bd2 b6 {Will most likely transpose to
the previous chapter.}) 6... Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 b6 8. cxd5 (8. Nf3 {Transposes to a
different chapter.}) 8... Nxd5 9. Qc2 Bb7 {We will go c5 and Nd7 next. As
usual, we want to play as energetically as possible.} 10. Nf3 c5 $1 11. dxc5
Nd7 $11) 5... d5 6. a3 {We saw 6.a3 in the Bd3 move order and this is pretty
similar. We cannot directly take on c4 here though as the bishop has not left
f1.} (6. Be2 dxc4 7. O-O c5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bxc4 a6 $11 {We will go Nbd7 and b5
next.}) 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 c5 8. Bb2 (8. Bd3 Qc7 $1 {Is the way to exploit
this move order.} (8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Qc7 {Will transpose back to the previous
chapter.}) 9. Nd2 (9. cxd5 cxd4 10. O-O dxc3 $11) 9... b6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O
Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 $11) (8. a4 {Another non-developing move from white.} Qa5 9.
Bd2 (9. Qc2 cxd4 10. exd4 Qc7 11. cxd5 exd5 $11 {We will continue with b6 and
Ba6 next. We have a clear target to play against- the pawn on c3.}) 9... Qc7 {
The queen did its job forcing the bishop to the passive d2 square. It cannot
go to a3 anymore.} (9... Ne4 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. Qc2 cxd4 12. exd4 Nxd2 13. Nxd2 {
1-0 (43) Caruana,F (2835) -Dominguez Perez,L (2758) Lichess.org INT 2020}) 10.
Be2 dxc4 11. O-O b6 12. Ne5 Rd8 13. Bxc4 Nbd7 14. Nxd7 Bxd7 $11 {We will go
for the e5 break soon. The position is balanced.}) (8. cxd5 exd5 {We are
threatening to go c4 next and close the center.} 9. dxc5 {Is maybe the best
but it has been played very few times and leads to a very comfortable position
for us.} (9. Bd3 $6 {Is the most popular move and a mistake.} c4 $1 {We saw a
similar position in the previous chapter too.} 10. Bc2 Ne4 $15) (9. Be2 $6 {
is also not good.} Ne4 10. Bb2 c4 $15) 9... Nbd7 10. c4 (10. Be2 Nxc5 11. O-O
Nfe4 $15) 10... Nxc5 11. cxd5 Bf5 $1 {The bishop is very well placed in this
diagonal.} (11... Nxd5 12. Qc2 $11 {0-1 (42) Kazmaier, D (2198) -Lenderman, A (
2623) Calgary 2015}) 12. Bc4 b5 13. Be2 Nxd5 $36) (8. Qc2 {This is a fusion of
many different systems which should not be good.} b6 {We want to get our
bishop to a6 immediately.} 9. cxd5 (9. Bd3 Ba6 10. cxd5 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Qxd5 $11)
(9. Be2 cxd4 10. cxd4 Ba6 {white has some problems due to his king still being
in the center.} 11. cxd5 (11. O-O Qc7 $36) 11... Qxd5 12. Bxa6 (12. O-O Rc8 $15
) 12... Qa5+ $1 13. Bd2 {We do not let him castle so easily.} Qxa6 $11) 9...
exd5 10. dxc5 (10. Bd3 {is a serious innaccuracy.} c4 $15) (10. Be2 c4 $1 {
We have seen this many times already.} 11. O-O Re8 $11 {We have a much clearer
plan on the queenside.}) 10... bxc5 11. c4 d4 $1 {We are fighting for the
initiative with the white king still in the center.} 12. Be2 (12. exd4 cxd4 13.
Be2 Re8 14. O-O Bg4 $11) 12... Bg4 13. O-O Nc6 $11 {Our active pieces
compensate for the bishop pair and the potential weakness on d4.}) 8... Nc6 {
We want to go Na5 next. It would be a dream to trade the light-squared bishops
and get the knight to c4.} 9. Rc1 (9. Bd3 b6 {Again the main point is to trade
the bishops with Ba6.} 10. O-O Ba6 11. cxd5 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Qxd5 13. c4 Qe4 $11)
(9. Be2 Na5 10. cxd5 Qb6 $1 11. Qc2 exd5 {We are threatening to go c4 next.}
12. dxc5 Qxc5 $11 {We have good control over c4.}) (9. Qc2 b6 10. cxd5 exd5 11.
c4 {This happened in the game between 1-0 (38) Carlsen, M (2859) -Gukesh, D (
2725) Chess.com INT 2022. He should have continued-} cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13.
Bxd4 Be6 14. cxd5 Qxd5 $11 {We want to make sure that white is unable to
develop the f1 bishop easily.}) 9... Na5 {We force him to release the tension.}
10. cxd5 exd5 {I hope you understand by now what our threat is here.} 11. dxc5
$8 (11. Be2 $2 c4 $19) (11. c4 $2 {is a big mistake due to} b5 $3 12. cxb5 c4
$17 {white is in big trouble with Rb8 to follow.}) 11... Be6 {We try to stop
the move d4.} 12. Nd4 (12. c4 {leads to mass simplifications after} dxc4 13.
Qxd8 Raxd8 14. Nd4 Ne4 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Bxc4 Nxc4 17. Rxc4 Nxf2 $11) 12... Ne4
13. c4 $1 {This is important to open the diagonal for the bishop.} (13. Be2 Qg5
$17) 13... Nxc4 14. Bxc4 Qa5+ {We are trying to keep the king in the center
for as long as possible.} 15. Bc3 Nxc3 16. Qd2 dxc4 17. Nxe6 (17. Qxc3 Qxc5 $11
) 17... fxe6 18. Qxc3 Qxc5 19. Qxc4 Qxc4 20. Rxc4 Rac8 {The endgame is
completely equal.} *


