{[%evp 0,36,24,24,24,27,22,22,23,0,0,2,2,-12,-22,-7,-12,-12,-12,4,11,10,17,17,
17,29,46,-15,-4,-19,13,-6,-21,-12,0,0,8,5,5]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
Qc2 {This is the Classical variation- a fierce competitor to 4.e3 in terms of
popularity. It is also very popular in modern times but the lines tend to be
more forcing here. So it is more popular amongst the theory-intensive players.
white wants to win the dark-squared bishop without weakening his pawn
structure. The obvious drawback is that the queen is forced to come out very
early.} O-O {We do our usual- castle first and keep options open.} 5. a3 {
This is the main direction here. white forces us to give up the dark squared
bishop but we are much ahead in development.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b6 {This is the
most played move but is a bit out of fashion these days at GM level. I think
this is simply because 6...d5 kind of kills the game while here we want to get
a complex middlegame. This also equalises completely and there have been
countless correspondence games here. We will usually go for the move d5 a bit
later.} (6... d5 {is the most solid option and does equalise cleanly. However
the lines usually lead to complete equality where we cannot fight for an edge.}
) 7. Nf3 {This is the solid way of playing which can arise via different move
orders.} (7. f3 d5 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gc8a6,Gd5c4] This is a much better version
for us as we can get the bishop directly to a6.}) 7... Bb7 8. e3 (8. g3 {
A strange mix between the Nimzo and Catalan. He wastes even more time to finish
development.} c5 $1 {The main point to note when we are playing c5 is to
ensure that d5 is not an issue for us. Here, we have nothing to worry about.}
9. dxc5 bxc5 10. Bg2 a5 $1 {We stop all ideas of b4. We will go a4 soon
getting a bind on the queenside.} 11. O-O d6 {I think this structure is the
best for playing for a win. We have the better pawn structure due to the clear
target along the 'b' file. Our d6 pawn can easily become an asset.} 12. Rd1 (
12. b3 Qc7 13. Rd1 Ra6 14. Bb2 Nbd7 $15 {[%cal Gf8b8,Ga6b6] We will go after
the b3 pawn soon.}) 12... Qc7 13. Bf4 e5 14. Bg5 Ne4 $36 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) 8...
d5 {We go d5 after having prepared it by going b6 and Bb7. Our next move is
going to be c5 to open up the center.} 9. b3 {white is trying to play it slow
with Bb2, Be2 and 0-0. The usual way here is to play Nbd7 and prepare the move
c5. But we have a more energetic option.} (9. cxd5 Bxd5 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O c5
$11 {Balck was very comfortable in 0-1 (24) Zeng,C (2597) -Harikrishna,P (2725)
Chess.com INT 2021}) (9. b4 {This is too ambitious. white wants to close down
the queenside with c5 and enjoy the space advantage but we will not allow that
easily.} a5 {We immediately fight back.} 10. c5 (10. b5 c5 11. dxc5 Ne4 $1 12.
Qc2 Nxc5 $11 {We will soon get our bishop to e4 and enjoy the juicy c5 square
for the knight.}) 10... axb4 11. axb4 Ne4 {We gain a free tempo.} 12. Qb2 Rxa1
13. Qxa1 Nd7 {We want to go Qa8 next before white is able to castle and bring
his rook into the game.} 14. Bd3 Qa8 15. Qxa8 Rxa8 $11) (9. Be2 {This is timid
and we play very energetically.} Ne4 10. Qc2 dxc4 11. Bxc4 c5 12. dxc5 Nd7 {
We would love to open up the 'c' file as quickly as possible.} 13. O-O (13.
cxb6 Nxb6 14. O-O Rc8 15. b3 Bd5 $11) 13... Nexc5 14. b4 Rc8 $1 {We may not
have the bishop pair right now but white will be forced to give up one of his
very soon.} 15. Bb2 Na4 16. Qxa4 Rxc4 $11) 9... c5 $1 {Why do we need to
prepare this? Lets make maximum use of our lead in development.} 10. dxc5 {
white takes our bait.} (10. Be2 {Is quite slow. The center comes under fire
quickly.} cxd4 11. exd4 dxc4 12. bxc4 Nc6 {We want to go Rc8 and Na5 next.} 13.
O-O Rc8 14. Bb2 Ne4 (14... Na5 {is also fine} 15. Ne5 Ne4 16. Qh3 Ng5 17. Qg4
f6 18. h4 fxe5 19. hxg5 Rf5 20. dxe5 Bxg2 21. Rfd1 Qe7 22. Qxg2 Rxg5 23. Bg4
Rg6 24. Rd6 Nxc4 25. Rxe6 Rxe6 26. Qd5 Rcc6 {1/2-1/2 (26) Turko,S (2383)
-Johnson,B (2311) ICCF email 2011}) 15. Qe3 Na5 16. c5 (16. Rac1 Nd6 $11 {
[%csl Rc4]}) 16... bxc5 (16... Bd5 $5 {We keep the b2 bishop restricted.} 17.
Bd3 f5 $11) 17. dxc5 Bd5 $11 {We are going to win the pawn on c5 next. white
has to prove his compensation. The position is dynamically balanced.}) 10...
Ne4 11. Qc2 Nd7 $1 {Our aim is to keep playing for the initiative as long as
the king is still in the center. We are not too worried about the material.}
12. cxb6 {This is the most ambitious and greedy move. We have no intention of
recapturing it yet.} (12. Bb2 Rc8 13. cxb6 dxc4 14. Bxc4 Nxb6 15. O-O Bd5 {
We win back the pawn with complete equality.} 16. Rfd1 Qe7 17. Bd4 Nxc4 18.
bxc4 Rxc4 19. Qb2 f6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (31) Gong,S (1893) -Xie,K (2224) Hainan 2023}
) 12... dxc4 13. bxc4 {white is okay with damaging his pawn structure to
maintain the pawn.} (13. Bxc4 Nxb6 14. O-O Rc8 $11 {We will go Bd5 and win the
pawn next.}) 13... Ndc5 (13... Nxb6 {is also fine and we will win the pawn back
soon.}) 14. Be2 Qf6 15. Ra2 (15. Bb2 Qg6 16. O-O Ng3 $17 {We are much better
here. I will leave it up to you to figure out the details.}) 15... axb6 16. O-O
Nc3 {We win the light-squared bishop and have terrific compensation due to the
bishop on b7.} 17. Bb2 Nxe2+ 18. Qxe2 Qg6 $44 {The knight on f3 can hardly move
anywhere.} *


