{[%evp 0,56,33,24,27,22,22,22,23,0,2,5,1,-7,-12,0,-11,-34,-36,-24,-40,-34,7,0,
35,-28,-14,1,7,24,19,20,20,16,23,19,33,41,44,34,22,44,29,28,28,28,22,38,35,0,0,
0,0,-22,0,0,-47,-32,-32]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+
6. Qxc3 b6 7. Bg5 {The main line by far and the critical move. This is the
drawback of having given up our dark-squared bishop. However, the fact remains
that white needs quite a few moves to get his king to safety and we need to
use this time to create our play.} Bb7 8. f3 {This is a pretty ambitious move
preparing to go e4 next. It does weaken the white king though. Also white
should be careful about ideas of Nxe4 exploiting the exposed bishop.} (8. Nf3 {
This does not fit in with the previous move.} d6 {This is the best way to play
for a win in these positions. We go for an asymmetrical pawn structure.} 9. Nd2
{white creates the option of going for the e4 plan. But I feel this wastes a
lot of time.} (9. e3 {white is playing pretty slowly allowing us to get
exactly what we want. We can go for either the e5 or the c5 plan.} Nbd7 10. Bd3
(10. Be2 h6 11. Bh4 g5 {We do the same as with Bd3. We want to utilise our
lead in development to the maximum.} 12. Bg3 Ne4 13. Qc2 f5 14. O-O-O Qf6 {
We will next bring our other rook to e8 and try to go for the e5 break.} 15.
Kb1 (15. Bd3 Rae8 $15 {[%cal Ge8e7,Ge6e5]}) 15... Rae8 $11) 10... h6 11. Bh4 g5
$5 {We are fighting for the initiative here.} (11... c5 {is the simpler way to
equalise.} 12. O-O Rc8 13. b4 cxd4 14. exd4 Bxf3 15. gxf3 e5 $11) 12. Bg3 Ne4
13. Qc2 f5 14. O-O-O (14. O-O Qf6 $40 {We have a dangerous attack brewing up
on the kingside.}) 14... Qe7 {We will go for the e5 break next.} 15. Ne1 e5 16.
f3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 e4 18. Be2 Kg7 $11 {The position is quite unclear with
chances for both sides.}) 9... Nbd7 10. f3 (10. e4 {does not work directly due
to} h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 $1 12. Bd3 a5 $15 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd4d5,Ga5a4] We gain some
space in the queenside before going for e5 next.}) (10. e3 h6 11. Bh4 e5 {
I think this is the perfect response to our opponent's slow play.} 12. Bd3 (12.
d5 Rc8 $15 {[%cal Gc7c6]}) 12... exd4 13. Qxd4 Qe7 $11 {We will bring our
other rook to e8. If white castles we can go for g5 and Nh5 followed by f5.})
10... h6 11. Bh4 Re8 $5 {This is a clever prophylactic move which has not been
played much. We keep all our options open and are ready to meet the move e4.}
12. e4 (12. e3 {does not make much sense now.} e5 13. d5 c6 $11) 12... c5 $1 {
The point of Re8 was to ensure that white is not able to meet c5 with d5
closing down the center. We want to try and blast open the central files with
the king on e1.} (12... e5 13. d5 $14) 13. Bd3 d5 $1 {We should always try to
make this move work. Here we make use of the bishop on h4.} 14. e5 Ne4 15. Bxd8
Nxc3 {This sequence with Ne4 was always a possibility but forcing the pawn to
e5 makes it a much better version for us.} 16. Bh4 (16. bxc3 Raxd8 $11) (16.
Bxb6 Nxb6 17. bxc3 cxd4 18. c5 dxc3 $11 {black it at least equal in the
resulting endgame.}) 16... cxd4 $1 {We sacrifice a piece for the central pawns!
} (16... Na4 {is also an interesting option.} 17. cxd5 cxd4 18. Bb5 Nac5 19. b4
Ba6 20. Bc6 Nd3+ 21. Kd1 N7xe5 {Here also we win the central pawns but for an
exchange.} 22. Bxa8 Rxa8 $44) 17. bxc3 dxc3 18. Nb3 Nxe5 19. Be2 dxc4 20. Nc1
Nc6 $1 {The knight is heading to its ideal square on d4.} 21. Bxc4 (21. Bd1 e5
22. Ne2 c2 23. Bxc2 Nd4 $44 {We will continue with g5 and Rad8.}) 21... Nd4 22.
O-O {We need to go for a forcing line here.} Nc2 23. Ra2 Ne3 24. Bb5 Nxf1 25.
Bxe8 Bd5 $1 {We gain a tempo against the rook.} 26. Ra1 Rxe8 27. Kxf1 c2 $44 {
The pawn on c2 gives us enough compensation for the piece. We do have three
pawns for the knight.}) (8. e3 h6 {We go for the same plan as the f3 variation.
This makes our job much easier to remember the ideas.} (8... d6 {is the main
line and also pretty good. I have played this also with good results. However
I feel our main line is more consistent with the lines we have seen.}) 9. Bh4
d5 $1 {Our plan is similar to the previous lines- we want to go c5 as quickly
as possible to make use of the king on e1.} 10. cxd5 (10. Nf3 Nbd7 {Here we
need to be a bit more circumspect as the pawn is on f2. We are ready to go c5
now.} 11. cxd5 Bxd5 12. Ne5 (12. Be2 c5 13. O-O (13. dxc5 g5 $1 $17) 13... g5
14. Bg3 Ne4 15. Qd3 Rc8 {We will go either c5 or f5 next. The position is
dynamically balanced.} 16. Rac1 c4 17. Qd1 b5 $11) 12... Nxe5 (12... g5 {
is also possible.}) 13. dxe5 Ne4 14. Bxd8 Nxc3 15. Be7 (15. Bxc7 Rfc8 16. Bd6
Ne4 17. f3 Nxd6 18. exd6 Bb3 $11 {We will win the d6 pawn by force.}) 15...
Rfe8 16. Bh4 Na4 {We have to give up the exchange unfortunately but we have
enough compensation.} 17. Bb5 Nxb2 18. Bxe8 Rxe8 19. f3 Nd3+ 20. Ke2 Nxe5 $11 {
We have two pawns for the exchange.}) (10. c5 {white tries to keep the
queenside closed. This has not been played much but I felt that it was pretty
natural.} bxc5 11. Bxf6 (11. Qxc5 Nbd7 12. Qc2 a5 {c5 is on the cards now. We
will then go a4 and get the queen to a5.} 13. Nf3 c5 14. dxc5 a4 $11) (11. dxc5
a5 {Our idea now is to play c6 and a4 to get a grip on the queenside. Then we
would go Ba6 to trade the bishops.} 12. Nf3 c6 13. Ne5 (13. Bd3 Nbd7 14. O-O
Ba6 $11) 13... a4 14. f3 Qa5 $11 {We can trade the queens and further weaken
the c5 pawn.}) 11... Qxf6 12. Qxc5 Rc8 {We would be better if we managed to
play Nd7 and c5. However, it is not going to be that easy.} 13. Rc1 (13. Nf3
Nd7 14. Qb5 Nb6 15. Be2 (15. Rc1 a5 $11) 15... c5 $1 {We take the chance to
get some activity.} 16. dxc5 Bc6 17. Qd3 (17. Qb4 Nc4 $36 {[%cal Ga8b8]}) 17...
Nc4 18. Qd4 Rab8 19. b4 a5 20. O-O axb4 21. axb4 Rxb4 $11) 13... a5 {We need
to trade bishops with Ba6 at some point.} (13... Nd7 14. Qb5 $1 Nb6 {Now again
getting c5 is not going to be easy.} 15. Nf3 a5 $11 16. Ne5 Qd8 {We have to
eventually go Nd7 and trade the knights.}) 14. Nf3 Qd8 {Now Nd7 and c5 is a
big threat but of course white will go-} 15. Ne5 c6 16. Be2 Nd7 17. Nxd7 Qxd7
$11 {[%cal Gb7a6] We will go Ba6 next and then play along the 'b' file.}) 10...
Bxd5 {We will either go c5 immediately or Nd7 followed by c5. Let's see if
white can do anything to stop it.} 11. f3 (11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Ne2 Rc8 $11) (11.
Nf3 c5 12. dxc5 Nbd7 13. cxb6 Qxb6 14. Qd4 Qb7 $44 {We will go Ne4 followed by
Ndc5 next.}) 11... c5 $1 {The most ambitious move especially when white has
already weakened his position with the move f3.} (11... Nbd7 12. Qd3 {[%cal
Ge3e4] white is able to get the move e4.} b5 $5 $11 {[%cal Gd5c4] This is also
fine for black. You can check this out.}) 12. dxc5 Nbd7 {tr} (12... bxc5 13.
Rd1 Nbd7) 13. e4 {The critical move. There has been only one game in this
position and it was my game played last year.} (13. cxb6 Qxb6 $11 {We have at
least enough compensation for the pawn.}) 13... Nxe4 {We enter a forcing line.}
14. Bxd8 Nxc3 15. Be7 Rfe8 16. Bd6 Na4 17. Bb5 Naxc5 18. Bxc5 Nxc5 19. Bxe8
Rxe8 {I was still in prep during this point. I felt that this position still
had a lot of life left even if my opponent reached all the way here. It ended
up being true as I soon got a promising edge.} 20. Nh3 {white gives up his b2
pawn after which we have two full pawns for the exchange.} (20. O-O-O {Is
probably the best move and we may have to force a draw here.} Rc8 21. Kb1 Bc4
22. Nh3 Bd3+ 23. Ka2 Bc4+ (23... Bc2 $11 {is another playable option.}) 24. Ka1
Be2 $11) 20... Nd3+ 21. Ke2 Nxb2 22. Rhc1 Bc4+ 23. Ke3 b5 $11 {I went on to
outplay my opponent in the game 0-1 (51) Jubin Jimmy (2259) -Arjun Kalyan (2477
) Pune 2022.}) 8... h6 9. Bh4 d5 {Once white has played f3 we want to open up
the center quickly. We plan to go c5 next.} 10. e3 (10. Rc1 {is too slow} c5
$15 11. dxc5 $6 d4 $1 $17) (10. cxd5 {This is supposed to be a concession as
it gives us the semi-open 'e' file for our rook. However, it does ensure that
the white king is more secure in the center.} exd5 11. e3 Re8 12. Bb5 $5 {
This came as a surprise in one of my games. white prevents the move c5 by
forcing us to go c6 and putting the bishop on a4. The drawback is that we can
get our bishop to the a6-f1 diagonal.} (12. Bf2 c5 $1 13. Bb5 cxd4 14. Qxd4 Nc6
$11 {black is very comfortable.}) (12. Nh3 {is pretty slow.} c5 $1 13. Bb5 Bc6
14. Be2 Qe7 15. Bf2 $6 Bd7 $17 {[%csl Rh3]}) 12... c6 13. Ba4 $1 Nbd7 14. Ne2
Ba6 $1 {We keep the king in the center. We will look to go for the move c5
next.} (14... Qe7 {This is the most played move but I do see the benefit of
this inclusion.} 15. Bf2 Ba6 16. Qd2 c5 17. Bd1 {[%cal Ge1g1] 1/2-1/ 2 (50)
Duda, J (2756) -Deac,B (2651) Terme Catez 2021}) (14... Ne4 {I panicked and
went for this endgame which is not great for us.} 15. Bxd8 Nxc3 16. Nxc3 Raxd8
17. Kf2 $14 {1-0 (54) Ioannidis,E (2466) -Arjun,K (2532) Cattolica 2022}) 15.
Qd2 (15. Bd1 c5 $1 {We want to take on d4 next.} 16. Qd2 (16. O-O Qe7 17. Bf2
cxd4 18. Qxd4 Ne5 $15 {[%cal Ge5d3]}) 16... cxd4 17. Nxd4 (17. exd4 Re6 $36)
17... Ne5 18. Be2 Bxe2 19. Qxe2 Nc4 {We end up winning the pawn on e3.}) (15.
Rc1 $146 Qe7 16. Bf2 c5 $1 {Our threat is simple- to go cd4 followed by Ne5.
white cannot castle due to our bishop.} 17. Qd2 cxd4 18. Nxd4 Rac8 $11) 15...
Bxe2 $1 16. Qxe2 b5 17. Bc2 Qa5+ $1 {This is the point- I would rather have
the queen on b6 than on e7. It is even better to force the move b4.} (17... c5
{1-0 (58) Kalesis, N (2447) -Mastrovasilis,A (2533) Athens 2006}) 18. b4 Qb6
19. Kf2 a5 20. Rhc1 Qd8 $11 {A clever move preparing Ng4+ which is not easy to
stop.}) 10... c5 $1 {As I have mentioned several times our main aim is to open
up the center as quickly as possible. We are often willing to sacrifice a pawn
to open the 'c' file.} 11. dxc5 (11. cxd5 {Here we have a lot of options. I
decided to go with the one which helps us keep winning chances open.} g5 $5 {
This does weaken the kingside but it keeps the queens on the board.} (11...
Nxd5 {leads to an equal endgame.} 12. Bxd8 Nxc3 13. Bxb6 axb6 14. bxc3 Ra5 15.
Kd2 Nd7 16. Bd3 Rfa8 17. Ne2 Rxa3 18. Rxa3 Rxa3 $11) (11... Bxd5 12. Nh3 (12.
dxc5 Nbd7) 12... cxd4 13. Qxd4 Nc6 14. Qf4 e5 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Qxf6 gxf6 $11)
12. Bg3 (12. Bf2 {is pretty similar.} Nxd5 13. Qd2 cxd4 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6]})
12... Nxd5 13. Qd2 Nc6 14. h4 (14. dxc5 Na5 $1 $15 {We exploit the weakness on
the queenside.}) 14... cxd4 15. exd4 Rc8 {We have brought almost all our
pieces into the game.} 16. hxg5 Qxg5 17. Qxg5+ hxg5 $11 {We have pretty good
chances to outplay our opponents in this endgame.}) 11... Nbd7 $1 {In the
spirit of our repertoire. We are happy to open as many lines as possible.} (
11... bxc5 {is also possible.}) 12. cxb6 {Again we have a choice between two
recaptures. I think a lot depends on how you feel about these kind of
positions.} (12. cxd5 g5 $1 {We want to take on d5 with the knight.} 13. dxe6
Nd5 14. Qd2 Nxc5 15. Rd1 gxh4 16. e4 Qf6 $5 {is an option to keep winning
chances alive.} (16... fxe6 {So far all the previous moves were more or less
forced. This should likely lead to a forced draw.} 17. exd5 Qxd5 18. Qxh6 Qe5+
19. Ne2 Rad8 20. Qg6+ Kh8 21. Qh6+ $11) 17. exd5 fxe6 18. d6 Rad8 $44) 12...
axb6 {I like this a bit more as it is easier to understand and the lines are a
bit more forcing.} (12... Qxb6 {You can check this out in more detail.} 13. c5
(13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Ne2 Rfd8 15. Nd4 dxc4 16. Bxc4 Rac8 17. b3 Bd5 18. Qb4 Bxc4
19. bxc4 f5 20. Rc1 f4 $11) 13... Qxc5 {the only way to keep fighting for win}
(13... Nxc5 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qxf6 Nb3 16. Qxh6 Nxa1 17. Bd3 f5 18. Qg6+ {
1/2-1/2 (18) Ferre Perez,A (2118) -Cvak,R (2322) ICCF email 2016}) 14. Bxf6
gxf6 15. Qxc5 Nxc5 16. b4 Nd7 17. Ne2 a5 18. b5 Rfc8 19. Nd4 Kf8 20. Bd3 Nc5
21. Bc2 Ke7 (21... e5 22. Nf5 a4 23. Nd6 Rd8 24. Nxb7 Nxb7 $11) 22. Ke2 Kd6 23.
Rhc1 Kc7 24. Bg6 Kb6 25. Bxf7 e5 26. Nc6 Nb3 27. Bxd5 Nxa1 28. Rxa1 Bxc6 29.
Bxc6 Rab8 $11) 13. cxd5 Rc8 14. Qd2 Ne4 $1 {We go for an endgame but our
initiative against the white king continues.} 15. Bxd8 Nxd2 16. dxe6 (16. Kxd2
Rfxd8 17. dxe6 Ne5+ 18. Ke1 fxe6 $44 {The rook is ready to penetrate to the 7th
rank soon.}) 16... Nxf1 17. exd7 Rcxd8 18. Kxf1 Rxd7 {We are two pawns down
here but we have enough compensation due to our activity and the open 'c' and
'd' files.} 19. Kf2 (19. Ke1 Re8 20. Nh3 Rxe3+ 21. Kf2 Rb3 22. Rhd1 Rxd1 23.
Rxd1 Rxb2+ $11) 19... Rd2+ 20. Kg3 Rc8 21. Nh3 Rc6 22. Nf4 g5 23. Nh5 Rcc2 24.
Rhg1 Kh7 {The knight lacks a good square on the board.} 25. Nf6+ Kg6 26. Ne4
Bxe4 27. fxe4 h5 28. h3 Rxb2 $11 *


