{[%evp 0,48,25,19,21,4,4,4,28,-6,0,0,11,19,-2,-2,7,-15,-12,-12,3,-1,14,13,13,
13,13,9,2,2,73,2,5,2,-31,-31,5,-12,46,48,30,24,24,20,23,18,37,37,29,29,29]} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. e4 {This is one of the most
frustrating lines in the Nimzo as it is very forcing and does not give us many
options. There are a few ways to equalise but we have to know a lot of theory
and white can force a draw. The flip side is that white also has to prepare a
lot of lines to go for this. Because of that we usually do not see many
lower-rated players going for this.} d5 6. e5 Ne4 7. Bd3 (7. cxd5 {Releasing
the tension early is not a great idea. it opens up the diagonal for our
light-squared bishop.} exd5 8. Bd3 c5 9. Nge2 (9. a3 Ba5 $1 {We have no reason
to take on c3 and improve white's pawn structure.} 10. Nge2 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bb6
12. Be3 Bxd4 13. Bxd4 Nc6 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Bc5 Re8 $11 {We win the e5 pawn
with a great position.}) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nd7 11. f4 (11. e6 {These ideas
are not that dangerous with the king still on e1.} Ndc5 12. exf7+ Rxf7 13. O-O
Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Bd6 $11) (11. Bf4 Re8 {We end up winning the e5
pawn easily.}) 11... Qh4+ 12. g3 Qh3 {We do not let white castle easily.} 13.
Bf1 Qh6 14. Bg2 Qa6 $1 $15 {He still cannot castle. We will go Nb6 next and
keep the pressure on.}) (7. a3 {This is a non-developing move. He forces us to
take on c3 but wastes valuable time.} Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 c5 9. Bd3 {transposes back
to the previous lines.} (9. f3 $2 {This seems to be a rare opening debacle for
Fabi. He probably mixed up his lines.} Qh4+ 10. g3 Nxg3 11. hxg3 Qxh1 12. Qf2
Qh5 13. Bd3 cxd4 $1 (13... f6 {0-1 (32) Caruana,F (2835) -So,W (2770) Lichess.
org INT 2020}) 14. cxd4 Nc6 {It looks like white can trap our queen but we
have prepared a cunning idea.} 15. g4 Nxe5 $1 16. Bc2 (16. Be2 Nxg4 17. fxg4
Qg6 18. Nf3 f6 $19) 16... Nxg4 17. fxg4 Qxg4 {We have 4 pawns (!!) and a rook
for two pieces. More importantly, we are able to go e5 and open up the central
files.} 18. Nf3 e5 $1 19. Nxe5 Qh3 20. Bb2 Qh6 $19) (9. Bb2 $6 {This leaves the
e1-a5 diagonal exposed.} cxd4 10. cxd4 Bd7 $1 {We do not rush with Qa5 but
prepare to go Ba4 next after that.} (10... Qa5+ {is very tempting but white is
better after-} 11. Ke2 $1 $16 {f3 is a big issue now.}) 11. Ne2 (11. Bd3 {
runs into} Qa5+ 12. Ke2 Ba4 $19 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) 11... Nc6 {We want to get our
knight to a5 and c4 soon, white is yet to finish his development.} 12. Rd1 Na5
$15) 9... cxd4 (9... Qa5 10. Ne2 cxd4 11. cxd5 exd5 12. f3 Nxc3 13. Nxd4 Ne4+
14. Ke2 $13 {1/2-1/2 (25) Wang,H (2737) -Wei,Y (2741) Danzhou 2019}) 10. cxd4 (
10. cxd5 exd5 11. cxd4 Nc6 12. Ne2 Bg4 $1 {We make use of the fact that white
has opened up the c8-h3 diagonal for the bishop.} 13. f3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Qh4+ 15.
Ng3 Nxd4 16. Qg2 Nc5 {We have a nice initiative here with the king in the
center.} 17. Bb1 Ncb3 18. Bb2 Nxa1 $11 {[%cal Gf7f6] The position is
dynamically balanced with f6 to follow.}) 10... Qa5+ 11. Kf1 (11. Bd2 {leads
to a completely equal endgame.} Qxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Nxd2 13. Kxd2 dxc4 14. Bxc4 Rd8
$11) 11... Nc6 12. Ne2 f6 $1 {We need to open the 'f' file for our rook.} 13.
Bxe4 (13. exf6 Nb4 $5 (13... Nxf6 $11 {is also fine.}) 14. axb4 Qxa1 15. fxg7
Rxf2+ 16. Ke1 Rf7 {The position remains complex but it is dynamically balanced.
}) 13... dxe4 14. exf6 Qf5 $1 {We bring our queen back into the game.} 15. Be3
Qxf6 {Our plan here is to go e5 followed by planting the knight on d4.} 16. Rd1
b6 {Now our bishop comes to a6 to put pressure on the c4 pawn.} 17. Kg1 Ba6 18.
h4 Na5 $36) 7... c5 8. Nf3 (8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nd7 10. Bf4
{Here the most critical line is definitely to enter the complications with Qh4.
I have tried a lot to find other options here which are less explored. I will
give some of my analysis but I did not find anything where our play is easy.} (
10. Bxe4 {gives us the valuable bishop and lets us equalise easily.} dxe4 11.
Qxe4 Qa5 12. O-O Qxe5 13. Qh4 a6 $11) 10... Qh4 {We are forcing further
weaknesses in white's position.} (10... Ndc5 {Is a decent option but I feel
the resulting lines are easier to play for white.} 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Nxd3
13. Qxd3 b6 14. cxd5 Qxd5 15. Rfd1 Bb7 16. c4 Qa5 17. Nb3 (17. Nb5 Bc6 18. a4 (
18. Nd6 $5 Nxd6 19. exd6 f6 20. Bd2 Qa4 21. Re1 e5 $11) 18... h6 19. Nd6 Rad8
20. Qe3 Nxd6 21. exd6 Rd7 22. Rdc1 {1/2-1/2 (22) Packroff,H (2216) -Darmanto,H
(2198) ICCF email 2017}) 17... Qb4 18. Be3 {[%cal Gf2f3]} Rfc8 19. Rac1 {
[%cal Gf2f3]} (19. f3 Nc3 {[%cal Gb4c4]}) 19... h6 $1 20. f3 Ng5 21. Nd4 Ba6
22. Qb3 Qe7 23. Rd3 {[%cal Gb3a4]} (23. Qa4 Bb7 $11) 23... Qb7 24. Nb5 Bxb5 25.
Qxb5 Rd8 26. Rcd1 (26. Rd6 Nxf3+ 27. gxf3 Qxf3 $11) (26. c5 Nxf3+ 27. gxf3 Qxf3
28. c6 Rd5 29. Qc4 b5 30. Qc2 Rad8 31. Bd4 Qe4 $11) 26... Qe7 27. c5 bxc5 28.
Rd7 Rxd7 29. Rxd7 Qe8 30. Bxc5 Rc8 31. Bd6 Rc1+ 32. Kf2 Rc2+ 33. Kg3 Rc3 $11)
11. g3 Qh5 (11... Qh3 {is not great due to} 12. O-O-O $14) 12. h4 $5 {This
became a new trend at some point but I think we have better chances in the
resulting positions. It is still something we should know well.} (12. Bxe4 $2 {
is very bad giving up the bishop for free.} dxe4 13. Qxe4 f6 $1 $17) (12. Be2 {
is a strange move. The only point I see is to go long castle but it is too
risky.} Qg6 13. a3 Bc5 14. Rd1 f6 $1 {A very common move to open up the center.
In contrast to the usual lines in the Nimzo we are the ones who are slightly
behind with our queenside development.} 15. cxd5 (15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Nxe6 Bxf2+
17. Kd2 Re8 $19 {was great for black in the game Parligras, M (2626)
-Naiditsch, A (2716) Sarajevo 2011.}) 15... Nxc3 16. bxc3 fxe5 17. dxe6 exf4
18. exd7 Bxd7 $11) (12. cxd5 {As usual this makes it easier for us to bring
our pieces out.} exd5 13. f3 {white is playing with fire here.} (13. O-O {
does not lead to much} Nxe5 14. Bxe5 (14. Be2 Ng4 $11) 14... Qxe5 15. Nf3 Qh5
16. Nxd5 Nd2 $1 17. Nxd2 Qxd5 $11 {We enjoy the bishop pair here.}) 13... Nec5
$1 $146 14. Bf5 (14. g4 Nxd3+ 15. Qxd3 Nxe5 $17) 14... Nxe5 $1 {We win the
pawn with some pretty tactics.} 15. Bxe5 Bxf5 16. Qxf5 Bxc3+ 17. bxc3 Qxf5 18.
Nxf5 Nd3+ 19. Ke2 Nxe5 $11 {white may win the pawn back but we are definitely
not worse.}) 12... Nxe5 13. Be2 Ng4 {Now the lines become forced for both
sides.} (13... Qg6 $5 {was recommended by Ganguly in his course. Also possible.
} 14. Bxe5 f6 15. h5 Qf7 16. Bf4 e5 17. cxd5 Qxd5 18. O-O-O (18. O-O Bxc3 19.
bxc3 exf4 20. gxf4 f5 $11) 18... Nxc3 19. bxc3 Ba3+ 20. Kb1 exd4 21. Qa4 Bf5+
22. Ka1 d3 23. Qxa3 Qc6 24. Bxd3 Bxd3 $11) 14. Bxg4 Qxg4 15. f3 Qh5 16. g4 Qg6
17. fxe4 e5 $1 {We just want to blast open the position. The white king will
want to castle queenside and we want to get our bishop to g4 before that.} 18.
O-O-O (18. Nf5 Qxg4 $19) (18. Bxe5 Re8 $1 19. O-O-O Bxc3 {Now white is the one
who has to be very careful.} 20. Bxg7 (20. bxc3 Bxg4 21. Rdg1 Rxe5 22. exd5 f5
$1 $11) (20. exd5 $6 Bxg4 $1 {a nice intermediate move.} 21. Qxg6 (21. Rdg1
Bxd4 22. Bxd4 Re4 $19) 21... hxg6 $15) 20... Bxg4 21. Qxc3 Rxe4 22. Rhg1 Qxg7
23. Nf5 Qxc3+ 24. bxc3 Kf8 $11) 18... Bxc3 19. Nf5 $1 {The line is pretty
crazy but we should be able to remember it if we understand the logic behind
the moves. white is threatening to go Ne7 or open up the 'g' file for the rook.
} Bxf5 20. gxf5 Qa6 21. Qxc3 (21. bxc3 exf4 22. cxd5 Qd6 {The position is
pretty complex still but we should be doing well if we can get a blockade in
the center.} 23. Rh3 Rac8 24. Rf3 Rc4 $36) 21... d4 $1 22. Qd2 (22. Qb3 exf4
23. Rxd4 Rac8 24. Kb1 Rfd8 25. Rhd1 Rxd4 26. Rxd4 Qc6 $11) 22... Qxc4+ 23. Kb1
exf4 24. f6 Qc6 25. Qxf4 Qxf6 $11 {Should lead to a draw here.} *


