{[%evp 0,48,25,19,21,4,4,4,28,-6,0,0,11,19,-2,-2,7,-15,-12,-12,3,-1,14,13,13,
13,13,9,2,2,73,2,5,2,-31,-31,5,-12,46,48,30,24,24,20,23,18,37,37,29,29,29]} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. e4 d5 6. e5 Ne4 7. Bd3 c5 8. Nf3 cxd4
9. Nxd4 Nd7 10. Bf4 Qh4 11. g3 Qh5 12. O-O g5 $1 13. cxd5 {This is the
critical move and it creates a complete mess on the board. I can look at the
position forever and understand nothing. You need to spend some time here to
understand the details. The good thing is that it is the same for white and he
has to deal with many more options from black. There are 3-4 ways to equalise
with black.} (13. Bxe4 $6 {Is not great giving up the bishop cheaply.} gxf4 14.
cxd5 Nxe5 $15 {We will go Ng4 next with a promising attack.}) (13. Be3 {
is pretty timid giving up the e5 pawn.} Nxe5 14. Be2 Qg6 15. cxd5 (15. Nxe4
dxe4 16. c5 Bd7 $11) 15... Nxc3 16. Qxg6+ {leads to an equal endgame.} Nxg6 17.
bxc3 Bxc3 18. Rac1 (18. Rad1 exd5 $15 {1/2-1/2 (31) Viani,A (2417) -Raahul,V (
2299) Nagpur 2023}) 18... Bxd4 19. Bxd4 exd5 $11) 13... gxf4 $5 {I recently
came across this move which is not the most popular but has been played by
strong players. There is a good chance your opponent is not too familiar with
these lines.} (13... Bxc3 {This is the move I had always prepared but never
faced this variation. I think it is a bit more complicated than our main line
but will give my analysis anyway.} 14. bxc3 (14. Be3 Nd2 15. Be2 g4 16. Qxc3
Nxf1 17. Rxf1 Nxe5 18. f4 gxf3 19. Nxf3 f6 20. Bc5 (20. Nd4 Ng4 21. Bxg4 Qxg4
22. Rf4 Qd1+ 23. Rf1 Qg4 $11) 20... Rf7 21. Nd4 Qh3 $11) 14... exd5 15. Be3 (
15. e6 gxf4 16. exd7 Bxd7 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Qxe4 {tr}) (15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. e6
gxf4 17. exd7 Bxd7 18. Qxe4 fxg3 19. fxg3 (19. hxg3 b6 20. Rfe1 (20. Qb7 Rad8
21. Qxa7 Bh3 22. Rfe1 Rxd4 23. cxd4 Qd5 $19) 20... Rad8 21. Qb7 Be6 22. Nxe6
fxe6 23. Qe7 Rd2 24. Qxe6+ Kh8 25. Rf1 Qc5 26. Qe1 Rd3 27. Kg2 Qd5+ 28. Kg1 Qc5
$11) 19... b6 20. Nf5 (20. Qe7 Bh3 21. Rf4 Rae8 22. Qh4 Qxh4 23. Rxh4 Bd7 (
23... Bc8 {0-1 (61) Sarana,A (2654) -Nakamura,H (2736) Chess.com INT 2020}) 24.
a4 Re5 $11 {[%cal Gf8c8]}) (20. Rae1 Rae8 21. Qf3 Qxf3 22. Nxf3 Bh3 $15) 20...
Rae8 21. Qd5 (21. Ne7+ Kg7 22. Qd4+ f6 23. Rae1 Bh3 24. Rf4 Rd8 25. Rh4 Qf3 26.
Qe4 Qxe4 27. Rexe4 Rd1+ 28. Kf2 Bd7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (35) Mamedyarov,S (2765)
-Efimenko,Z (2706) Ningbo 2011 CBM 144 [Krasenkow,M]}) 21... Bxf5 22. Rxf5 Qe2
23. Raf1 Qe3+ 24. R1f2 Qe1+ 25. Kg2 Qe4+ 26. Qxe4 Rxe4 $11) 15... Nxe5 16. f3
Nc5 $1 17. Bf5 (17. Be2 Nc4 18. Bxc4 dxc4 19. Nc6 bxc6 (19... Nd3 20. Ne7+ Kg7
21. Qa4 f6 22. Qxc4 Ne5 $11) 20. Bxc5 Re8 $11) 17... f6 18. Kg2 (18. h4 g4 19.
fxg4 Nxg4 20. Qd1 Kh8 $1 21. Ne6 Bxe6 22. Qxg4 Qxg4 23. Bxg4 Bxg4 24. Bxc5 $11)
(18. Rad1 b6 19. Kg2 Ba6 $1 (19... g4 20. fxg4 Nxg4 21. Bg1 Re8 22. Rf4 Ne3+ (
22... Ne5 $11) 23. Bxe3 Rxe3 24. Bxc8 Rxc8 25. Rh4 $18 {1-0 (51) Budisavljevic,
L (2508) -Van Foreest,L (2543) Riga 2021}) 20. Rfe1 g4 $1 21. fxg4 Nxg4 $11) (
18. Qg2 Nc4 19. Rae1 (19. Bf2 Qf7 20. g4 Re8) 19... Re8 20. Bf2 Bxf5 21. g4 Qg6
22. Nxf5 Nd3 $17 {1/2-1/2 (68) Miljkovic,M (2466) -Saric,A (2540) Struga 2021})
18... Re8 19. g4 Qf7 20. h4 Ng6 21. Bxg6 Qxg6 22. Nf5 b6 23. hxg5 fxg5 24. Rh1
(24. Rae1 Ba6 25. Bxc5 Bxf1+ 26. Kxf1 bxc5 27. Ne7+ Rxe7 28. Qxg6+ hxg6 29.
Rxe7 Kf8 {1/2-1/2 (29) Krutous,A (2335) -Lemutov,I (2399) ICCF 2020} 30. Re5
Re8) 24... Re5 $1 25. Bxc5 (25. Nh6+ Kf8 26. Nf5 Bxf5 27. gxf5 Qxf5 28. Qxf5+
Rxf5 29. Rxh7 Re8 30. Bxc5+ bxc5 31. Rb1 Kg8 32. Rbb7 Re2+ 33. Kg3 Re3 34.
Rbg7+ Kf8 35. Kg4 Rexf3 36. Rd7 R3f4+ 37. Kg3 Rf3+ 38. Kg4 {1/2-1/2 (38)
Pundak,M (2358) -Duchardt,A (2363) ICCF 2019}) (25. Rh6 Bxf5 26. Rxg6+ Bxg6 27.
Qd1 Nd3 28. Bd4 Re2+ 29. Qxe2 Nf4+ 30. Kf2 Nxe2 31. Kxe2 $11) 25... bxc5 26.
Rh6 Qf7 (26... Bxf5 27. Rxg6+ Bxg6 28. Qf2 $18) 27. Ng3 Rb8 28. Qf2 Qf4 29.
Rah1 (29. Qc2 Qf7 30. Qf2 {1/2-1/2 (30) Shpakovsky,A (2545) -Plomp,M (2554)
ICCF 2021}) 29... Re3 {[%cal Gb8b2]} 30. Nh5 Qe5 31. Nf6+ Kf8 32. Nxh7+ Ke7 33.
Qg3 Re2+ 34. Kh3 Rb6 35. Qxe5+ Rxe5 36. Rh5 Rg6 $11) 14. dxe6 (14. Nxe4 {
does not lead to much after} exd5 15. Nf6+ Nxf6 16. exf6 Bh3 $11 {[%cal Ga8e8]}
) 14... Nxe5 {Again this is not the most common move which is again in our
favour. We want to get our knight to g4.} 15. Nxe4 fxe6 16. f3 (16. gxf4 Rxf4 {
The position starts getting crazy from here.} (16... Qg4+ 17. Kh1 Qxf4 18. f3
Kh8 $11) 17. Kh1 Kh8 18. Rg1 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 Be7 $1 {The bishop is well placed
covering some crucial squares on the kingside.} 20. Rac1 Bd7 21. Qg3 (21. Rc7
Qd5 22. Rxd7 Qxd7 23. Qg3 Qxd4 24. Qxf4 Rf8 $11) 21... Rf7 {The position looks
a bit dangerous for us but it is actually the same for white. If our bishop
gets to the h1-a8 diagonal it will be a huge issue for white.} 22. Rc7 Bh4 $8 {
The only move.} 23. Qc3 {The lines here are completely crazy with the stakes
high for both sides.} (23. Qg4 {this simplifies the position to an equal
endgame.} Qxg4 24. Rxg4 e5 25. Rxh4 exd4 26. Ng5 Re7 $11) 23... e5 24. Nd6 Rf6
25. Rxd7 Bxf2 26. Rc1 (26. N4f5 Bxg1 27. Nf7+ Rxf7 28. Qxe5+ Kg8 29. Qg3+ Kh8
$11) 26... Rg8 27. Ne6 Qg6 {white has two very imaginative options here. You
can have fun analysing these lines:) I do not think it makes sense to memorise
all this. If you analyse it a bit you can manage it over the board.} 28. Rxh7+
$5 (28. Rg7 Rxg7 29. Nxg7 Kxg7 30. Qxe5 Kh6 31. Ne4 Rf5 $11) 28... Qxh7 29.
Qxe5 Bh4 30. Qd4 Qh5 31. Nf7+ Kh7 32. Qe4+ Rgg6 33. Qxb7 Rxe6 {1/2-1/2 (33)
Boos,M (2427) -Jugl,P (2370) GER email 2021}) 16... fxg3 17. Nxg3 (17. hxg3 Ba5
$1 {A very nice regrouping of pieces to bring the bishop in contact with the
center.} 18. Kg2 Bb6 19. Qc3 (19. Ne2 {This leads to a forced draw} Nxf3 20.
Nf4 Rxf4 21. gxf4 Nh4+ 22. Kh1 Nf3+ 23. Kg2 Nh4+ 24. Kh1 Nf3+ 25. Kg2 Nh4+ {
1/2-1/2 (25) Peng,L (2535) -Fedorchuk,S (2589) Purtichju 2023}) 19... Bd7 20.
Rh1 Bxd4 {The position simplifies now.} 21. Rxh5 Bxc3 22. bxc3 Rxf3 23. Bc2 Rf5
$11 {Should likely lead to a draw.}) 17... Qh6 18. Be4 (18. Rad1 Nxd3 19. Qxd3
a5 $1 {[%cal Ga8a6] Time to bring the rook into the game via a6. We can then
play e5 and swing the rook to the kingside.} 20. a3 Be7 21. Kh1 Ra6 $11) 18...
Qd2 $1 {We simplify the position even at the cost of the pawn. We do have the
bishop pair.} 19. Bxh7+ (19. Qxd2 Bxd2 $11) 19... Kh8 {The problem for white
is that he is not able to preserve the extra pawn. We have too many threats.}
20. Rfd1 (20. Qe4 Bd6 {Rf4 is a threat now.} 21. Nb5 Rf4 22. Rad1 Nxf3+ $1 23.
Qxf3 Bc5+ 24. Kh1 Rxf3 $11 {will lead to a lot of simplifications.}) 20...
Nxf3+ 21. Nxf3 Qe3+ 22. Qf2 Bc5 $1 23. Qxe3 Bxe3+ 24. Kg2 Kxh7 $11 {The
endgame is even but we have the potential to take over with our bishop pair.} *


