{[%evp 0,38,27,24,22,22,22,12,23,0,-6,-8,-14,-45,-2,-11,2,1,3,-3,7,0,-8,0,0,
-12,2,8,26,24,19,9,21,20,16,13,9,13,24,27,29]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
Qc2 O-O 5. Bg5 {This is a bit early and over-ambitious. white is preparing the
move e4 but we will fight back in the center quickly.} (5. Nf3 {This will be
checked in the next part as it transposes to the 4.Nf3 variation.}) (5. Bd2 {
This is a strange move in this variation. The point of Qc2 was to recapture on
c3 with the queen and now why does white get his bishop to d2?} d5 6. e3 b6 7.
Nf3 (7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nf3 Re8 {This transposes to the e3, Bd2 chapter.}) 7...
dxc4 (7... Re8 $5) 8. Bxc4 Bb7 $11 {We will be going c5 next. The position
will simplify soon.}) 5... c5 $1 {This break is pretty effective as long as
white is unable to go d5 and clamp down on the center.} 6. dxc5 (6. d5 {
white has overextended his position with his pieces yet to be developed.} d6 7.
O-O-O h6 8. Bh4 Bxc3 $1 {We are going to get our knight to b4 next. Also, the
queen is not that well placed on c3.} 9. Qxc3 g5 10. Bg3 Na6 $15 {We have a
nice edge with Nb4 and b5 to follow.}) (6. e3 {is pretty tame.} cxd4 7. exd4 h6
8. Bh4 Nc6 9. Nf3 d5 {I believe that these lines are easier to play for us as
we have several promising ideas. We can go g5 and Ne4 or go e5 and blast open
the center. The white king lacks a good square on the board.} 10. a3 (10. Rd1
g5 11. Bg3 Ne4 12. Bd3 f5 $36 {white has to go h3 and accept a bad pawn
structure.}) 10... Bxc3+ {usually black would preserve the bishop but here he
is much ahead in development and can break open the center} 11. bxc3 (11. Qxc3
{runs into} g5 12. Bg3 Ne4 $17 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gc8d7]}) 11... e5 $1 {We have
achieved our dream of opening up the center.} 12. dxe5 (12. cxd5 Qxd5 13. Bxf6
gxf6 {Our kingside is a bit exposed but white does not have the firepower to
exploit it. He has to first get his king to safety.} 14. Be2 exd4 15. O-O Qc5
$15) 12... Re8 13. O-O-O (13. Be2 Nxe5 14. O-O Nxc4 $11 {The best white can
hope for is to win the pawn back.}) 13... Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Rxe5 15. cxd5 Bd7 $40 {
[%csl Rc1][%cal Ga8c8,Gd8e7] We have a big initiative brewing up on the
queenside with Rc8 next.}) (6. Nf3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 h6 8. Bh4 e5 {We play
energetically making use of our lead in development.} (8... Nc6 $11) 9. Bxf6 (
9. Ndb5 {Will be met with} g5 $1 10. Bg3 a6 11. Na3 d5 12. cxd5 Qxd5 $15 {
The bishop on g3 is out of the game and we have a big lead in development.}) (
9. Nb3 d6 10. e3 Be6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ga8c8,Rc8c2] The c4 pawn will come under a
lot of pressure.}) 9... Qxf6 10. Ndb5 d5 $1 {We open up the diagonal for the
bishop. Also, we ensure that the knight cannot jump to d5.} 11. cxd5 a6 12. Na3
(12. Nc7 Ra7 $19 {The knight is just trapped here.}) 12... b5 {We have a
simple threat of Ba5 followed by b4 which is very hard to handle.} 13. Nab1 e4
14. Qxe4 Ba5 $36 {Bf5, Nd7 and Rc8 are coming next. It is not going to be easy
for white.}) 6... Na6 $1 {We want to bring our knight to c5 followed by Ne4.
The bishop will likely go to b7.} 7. a3 (7. Nf3 Nxc5 8. a3 {I think this is
just a waste of tempo as we were intending to take on c3 soon.} (8. Nd2 {
white stops Ne4 ideas but he has played too passively.} h6 9. Bh4 b6 (9... d5
$5) 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Qxc3 Bb7 $11 {We want to go d5 next and it is not going to
be pleasant for white.} 12. f3 {1/2-1/2 (13) Istratescu,A (2590) -Nisipeanu,L (
2678) Tusnad 2004} (12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qxf6 gxf6 {with a better version of the
main line}) 12... d5 $36 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ga8c8]}) 8... Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 Nfe4 $1 {
At first sight the trade of queens looks good for white but we can trap the
rook on a1.} 10. Bxd8 Nxc3 11. Be7 Nb3 $1 12. Bxf8 Kxf8 13. Rd1 Nxd1 14. Kxd1
d5 $15 {We have a slightly better position due to the activity of our pieces.
We will try to create quick play against the white king.}) 7... Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3
Nxc5 9. Bxf6 {white is forced to go into an endgame as we were threatening the
move Ne4. The endgame is dynamically balanced with our activity compensating
for the worse pawn structure.} (9. f3 $6 {fails to do its job.} Nfe4 $1 10.
Bxd8 (10. fxe4 Qxg5 $15) 10... Nxc3 11. Be7 Nb3 $17) (9. e3 Nce4 $11) 9... Qxf6
10. Qxf6 gxf6 {We have two plans here- to go b6, Bb7 against everything or to
go for the move a5.} 11. b4 (11. e3 a5 $1 $11 {[%cal Ga8a6,Ga6b6] Our plan of
Ra6-b6 is very dangerous here. white has to be careful.}) (11. Rd1 a5 {I like
this plan more gaining some space on the queenside.} 12. e3 Na4 {We want to
create some weakness on the queenside for white. We would be happy to open up
the 'a' file.} (12... a4 $11 {followed by Ra6-b6 is also pretty good.}) 13. b3
(13. Rd2 Ra6 $11 {[%cal Ga6b6]}) 13... Nc5 14. b4 axb4 (14... Na4 {is also
fine.} 15. Rc1 b6 16. Ne2 Bb7 17. Nf4 Rfc8 18. Be2 b5 19. c5 axb4 20. axb4 d6
21. Bxb5 dxc5 22. bxc5 Rxc5 23. Rxc5 Nxc5 {1/2-1/2 (33) Shankland,S (2727)
-Wei, Y (2729) Danzhou 2018}) 15. axb4 Na6 16. Ra1 (16. Rb1 Nc7 $11 {We will go
d5 next and equalise.}) 16... d6 17. b5 Nc7 18. Rxa8 Nxa8 $11 {We will plan to
go Nb6, e5 and Be6 targeting the c4 pawn. We can also try to utilise the 'a'
file with our rook.}) 11... Na4 {[%cal Ga7a5] I am always a bit uncomfortable
with the knight on a4 but it is doing pretty well. It's hardly possible for
white to attack the knight.} 12. e3 (12. Nf3 a5 13. e3 d6 {transposes.}) (12.
e4 a5 13. Kd2 d5 $1 {A very typical idea when the king is stuck in the center.}
14. exd5 Nb6 $1 $11 {We create a threat of axb4 and win the pawn on d5.}) 12...
d6 {We want to go e5 followed by Be6 and put pressure on c4. I like to keep the
b6 square open for the knight.} 13. Nf3 (13. O-O-O d5 $1 {The king is going to
come under a lot of pressure along the 'c' file.} 14. cxd5 Bd7 15. dxe6 Rfc8+
16. Kd2 fxe6 $44 {Nc3-e4 is a threat now. The rook will infiltrate along the
'c' file.}) 13... a5 14. Be2 e5 15. Nd2 f5 {We stop the move Ne4.} 16. Nb3 (16.
O-O Nc3 {The knight becomes a nuisance for white now.} 17. Bd3 Be6 18. Rfc1
axb4 19. axb4 Na2 20. Rcb1 Ra3 $11 {[%cal Gf8a8]}) 16... b6 {We maintain the
tension on the queenside. We can always decide to open up the 'a' file.} 17.
Rc1 Be6 18. O-O Rfc8 19. Nd2 Kf8 $11 {I like black more here due to our king.
Also, we have the plan of taking on b4 and going for the move b5. Our central
pawns look pretty good.} *


