{[%evp 0,52,23,23,24,-11,-6,6,26,30,30,28,28,18,17,25,10,10,26,24,45,30,65,38,
30,19,17,25,25,43,48,25,29,29,26,26,48,39,34,37,28,25,42,41,41,36,27,33,33,29,
24,16,19,8,6] How to continue here?} 12... Bc7 $1 {This is one of our major
plans in this system- we take on d4 after making sure that the bishop on c1
cannot jump to either g5/f4. Next, we will go Ne7 and b6, Bb7.} 13. Re1 {
This position is important to remember because we have to choose correctly
between b6 and Ne7.} (13. Rd1 {white is preparing to go d5 soon.} Ne7 {We
first stop the move d5.} 14. Ne5 b6 {We want to bring another piece in contact
with the d5 square.} 15. Qf3 Rb8 16. Nb5 Bb7 17. Qe2 Ra8 $11) (13. Bd2 b6 14.
Rfe1 Bb7 15. d5 {white decided to simplify the position in the center.} exd5
16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Qxd5 18. Bxd5 Rad8 $11) 13... Ne7 {We first get better
control over d5 and get ready to jump to f5, d5 or g6.} (13... b6 $6 {looks
very natural but white has this amazing move-} 14. g4 $1 $36) 14. Bd2 (14. Ne5
{white is ready to meet b6 with Qf3.} Nf5 {We attack the weak pawn on d4.} (
14... b6 {allows} 15. Qf3) 15. Be3 a6 16. a4 b6 17. Rad1 Bb7 $11) 14... b6 15.
Rad1 (15. Ne5 Bb7 16. Nb5 Bd5 17. Bb4 Bxc4 18. Qxc4 Bb8 {Our pieces look
passive but white's pieces are going to get pushed back slowly with a6 and b5
next.} 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Nc3 Qb7 $11) 15... Bb7 16. Ne5 a6 17. Bc1 b5 18. Ba2
Rc8 {We have managed to get all of our pieces in their ideal squares while
white has not managed to create anything on the kingside. The longer the game
continues the more our advantage will be visible- the IQP is going to be a
long-term issue.} 19. Bb1 Ba5 20. Ng4 Ng6 $11 *

