{[%evp 0,15,19,26,-4,13,-12,-20,-46,-31,-34,-52,-95,-47,-29,-20,-23,-22] What
is the typical idea here?} 9... c5 {Should almost be blitzed out if we see the
move f3. white is the one who has to be careful now.} 10. Qe1 (10. g4 {does
not achieve much} Nc6 11. Kh1 b6 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7]}) (10. Nb5 Bf8 11. dxc5 Bxc5
12. Nbd4 Nc6 {black is already slightly better here.} 13. Bd2 Bd7 (13... Qb6 {
1/2-1/2 (89) Gelfand,B (2736) -Carlsen,M (2714) Moscow 2007}) 14. Rc1 Bb6 15.
Re1 h5 $15 {A very typical move in such positions. We will go h4 next soon.})
10... b6 {We prepare the move Ba6 and also free up the bishop on d6.} 11. Qh4
Ba6 12. Bc2 $5 {white is desperate to start something on the kingside but it
is pretty slow and we have quick counterplay in the center.} cxd4 13. exd4 Bxe2
14. Bg5 (14. Nxe2 Rxe2 15. Bxh7+ Kf8 $17) 14... Nbd7 $1 {We keep our pawn
structure intact.} 15. Nxe2 h6 $1 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 $15 {We have the better bishop
and a safer king.} *

