{[%evp 0,19,15,12,6,11,12,19,-15,19,18,19,19,69,5,2,-20,-14,-10,3,-3,-9] How
to continue here?} 7... Bd6 $1 {I think this is more precise as we are ready
to go b6 and c5 immediately.} (7... Re8 $6 {allows an extra option of} 8. Bd2
Bd6 9. Rc1 {[%cal Gc3b5]}) 8. Nb5 (8. Bd2 b6 9. Rc1 c5 10. O-O Re8) (8. O-O Re8
{A very flexible move again keeping all options open. white has many different
moves here.}) 8... Be7 9. O-O (9. Bd2 b6 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5]}) 9... Re8 {We do
not need to go c6 just yet.} 10. Qc2 (10. Bd2 a6 11. Nbc3 c5 {white's position
is quite passive and we have a good version of the IQP.} 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Rc1
Nc6 $11) 10... c6 11. Nbc3 Bd6 12. Bd2 (12. f3 c5 $11 {It is a well-known rule
that we should for the c5 break as soon as white weakens his kingside with the
move f3.}) (12. Ng3 h5 $5 $11 {Another common idea to deal with Ng3!}) 12... b6
$1 {We follow our usual plan against Nge2- b6 and c5 as quickly as possible.
The knight remains on b8 as it can head directly to c6.} 13. Nf4 (13. f3 c5 $11
) (13. e4 {does not work due to} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxh2+ $15) (13.
Rad1 Ba6 {It makes a lot of sense to get the bishops off the board first. We
will go for the move c5 very soon.} 14. f3 c5 15. a3 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Nc6 $11)
13... Ba6 {With the knight on f4 we can change our plans a bit. The knight is
not doing much there when our pawn is still on c6.} 14. Bxa6 Nxa6 15. Nce2 Qd7
16. Rac1 Rac8 $11 *

