{[%evp 0,11,-17,-17,-14,-17,-17,-30,3,3,3,3,3,9] How to continue here?} 13...
Ne7 {We want to bring the knight to f5 next. The only thing to keep in mind
here is the move Bg5 but it does not pose many problems.} 14. Bg5 (14. Rc1 Nf5
$11) 14... Nf5 {This is the most solid move immediately attacking the pawn on
d4. white is practically forced to go for} (14... Ng6 {I like this move more
as it is more fighting.} 15. h4 {The critical test.} (15. d5 {is not as
effective and we can just go for-} h6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. dxe6 fxe6 18. Qd7 {
looks strong but it met with} Bxg2 $1 19. Qxe6+ Qxe6 20. Bxe6+ Kh7 21. Kxg2
Nf4+ $11 {The position simplifies but black has slightly better chances in the
endgame due to the pawn structures on the kingside.}) 15... h6 16. h5 (16. Bxf6
{is a terrible move} Qxf6 $17) 16... Ne7 17. Bxf6 gxf6 {We should be happy to
see the doubled pawns as we usually want to keep the game going.} 18. Re1 f5
$11) 15. d5 {which leads to a lot of simplifications.} exd5 16. Bxd5 (16. Qd3
d4 $11) 16... Bxd5 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Qxd5 Rad8 $11 {The position is quite
symmetrical and completely equal.} *

