{[%evp 0,27,34,33,26,25,13,13,13,13,17,16,12,12,4,5,2,15,17,31,20,21,19,0,0,0,
0,0,0,0] How to continue here?} 9... Na6 $5 {This is an interesting idea aimed
against the knight on f4. We want to bring our knight to e6 and at the same
time keep the rook on f8 (the usual plan is to go Re8, Nd7-f8) .} 10. O-O Nc7
11. f3 {This is the right time to go f3 as the knight has already been
rerouted to c7.} (11. Bd2 Ne6 12. Nxe6 Bxe6 $11) (11. b4 {This makes some
sense now as we cannot get the knight to c4 easily. However, we will still
prepare the move a5 on the queenside.} Bd6 12. f3 (12. b5 {is too early} cxb5
13. Nxb5 Nxb5 14. Bxb5 Bf5 $15) 12... a5 $1 13. b5 Re8 $11 {white is nowhere
close to attacking the pawn on c6.}) 11... Ne6 (11... Re8 {is the usual plan
to prepare c5 which is also fine.} 12. Bd2 c5 $11) 12. Nxe6 (12. Nfe2 {does
not make much sense to me as he has just wasted two full moves.} Re8 13. Bd2 c5
14. Be1 {0-1 (39) Martinovic,S (2604) -Santos Ruiz,M (2488) Batumi 2018} cxd4
15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. exd4 Bd7 {The position is roughly balanced.}) 12... Bxe6 {
The exchange of knights is usually in our favour as the center is more exposed
for white.} 13. Bd2 Re8 {We are going to go for the move c5 next and put more
pressure on the e3 pawn.} 14. Rc1 (14. Be1 c5 15. Bf2 cxd4 16. exd4 a6 $11 {
The position is roughly balanced here. We can go for Nh5 next and try to play
on the kingside.}) 14... Rc8 15. Na4 {white decides to stop the plan of c5.}
Bd6 16. Qe2 Nd7 {Our plan is now to go b5 and kick the knight back. We can
also play c5.} 17. b4 {This is not something that white is too happy to play.}
b6 18. e4 dxe4 19. fxe4 Qh4 {white has to sense the danger and allow us to
force the draw here.} 20. g3 Bxg3 21. hxg3 Qxg3+ 22. Kh1 Qh3+ $11 *

