{[%evp 0,23,22,36,41,56,41,59,68,83,36,30,34,34,26,37,34,52,43,70,48,59,37,47,
28,54] How to continue here?} 8... Bd6 $1 {We have seen this idea before- we
immediately bring the bishop back, not allowing Rc1 and Nb5 ideas.} 9. O-O (9.
Rc1 c5 $11) (9. Ne5 c5 10. O-O Bb7 11. f4 Nc6 12. Ne2 cxd4 13. exd4 Ne4 $11)
9... Re8 $1 {We stop both e4 and Ne5 ideas. We maintain the option of going
for the move Ba6 anytime.} (9... c5 10. e4 $1 $16) 10. Nb5 {white kicks the
knight back to get the e5 square for the knight.} (10. Qc2 {I faced this in a
classical game last year. It is logical to control e4 but it will come under a
lot of fire along the 'c' file. Moreover, Nc6 now comes with a tempo.} c5 $1
11. e4 {white tries to open up the center.} (11. dxc5 bxc5 {This hanging pawns
structure is great for us and the bishop on d2 is useless.}) 11... c4 12. e5 (
12. Be2 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 $6 {Happened in the game 0-1 (78) Raahul, V (2478)
-Arjun,K (2506) Gurugram 2022. I could have got an edge after} Bf5 $15) 12...
cxd3 13. Qxd3 Bb4 14. exf6 Ba6 15. Nb5 Bxd2 16. Nxd2 Qxf6 {black is very
comfortable here with Nc6 to follow.}) (10. Re1 Bb7 {We keep control over e4.}
11. Qc2 Na6 $1 {[%cal Ga6b4] We kind of gain a tempo by threatening to go Nb4.
The knight will eventually come to e6 via c7.} 12. a3 c5 13. e4 {white tries
to blast open the center but we do have enough pieces to fight back.} (13. dxc5
bxc5 $11) 13... cxd4 14. Nxd5 Nc5 15. Bg5 Rc8 $11 {The position is dynamically
balanced here. We are threatening to go for the move Ne4 next.}) (10. Rc1 c5 {
We have got everything that we wanted in time. white has to be careful now as
we can very easily take over the initiative. The dangerous plan of Ne5 has been
stopped.} 11. Bb5 (11. dxc5 {Should be a good sign for us with the bishop on
d2.} bxc5 12. Qa4 a6 13. Rfd1 Nbd7 $11) (11. Nb5 {A desperate attempt to get
the knight to e5.} Bf8 12. Ne5 Bb7 13. f4 $6 {This is too weakening for white
as he is unable to maintain good control over d4.} (13. a4 a6 14. Nc3 Nc6 $36)
13... Nc6 {If white gets a couple of tempi we would be toast but as it is he
is unable to defend d4.} (13... Ba6 14. a4 Bb7 15. Be1 {was great for white in
the game 1/2-1/2 (79) Kovalenko, I (2663) -Neiksans, A (2552) Riga 2019}) 14.
Be1 a6 15. Nc3 cxd4 16. Nxc6 {This is a huge concession.} Bxc6 17. exd4 Ne4 $17
) 11... Bd7 {white is trying to misplace the bishop to d7 but it does not help
much.} 12. b3 h6 {We will keep maintaining the tension. We can always go for
the move Nc6.} (12... a6 13. Bxd7 Nbxd7 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Ne2 $14 {1/2-1/2 (34)
Anton Guijarro,D (2675) -Giri,A (2764) chess24.com INT 2020:}) 13. h3 Nc6 14.
Re1 cxd4 15. exd4 Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 a6 $11) 10... Bf8 11. Ne5 Ba6 {This is the
benefit of our move order. The exchange of light-squared bishop is in our
favour.} 12. Be1 (12. Rc1 c5 {[%cal Gc5c4]} 13. a4 Bb7 $11 {We will go a6 next
followed by Nc6. The inclusion of a4 and a6 should definitely be in our favour.
}) 12... c6 13. Nc3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Qc8 {The queen will be well placed on b7 to
play on the queenside. The knight will go to d7.} 15. Rc1 Qb7 16. f4 Nbd7 17.
Bh4 {All this happened in the game 0-1 (62) Prohaszka, P (2585)
-Praggnanandhaa, R (2690) Budapest 2023. Even better here was} b5 18. Bxf6 Nxf6
19. Rc2 Nd7 $11 {We prepare to go f6 next.} *

