{[%evp 0,33,-55,-29,-29,-24,-24,-24,-24,-24,-24,-24,-176,-69,-123,-123,-123,
-130,-80,-65,-65,-73,-82,-65,-74,-26,-26,-31,-34,-43,-44,-64,-67,-55,-38,-37]
How to continue here?} 11... Re8 $5 {This is a clever prophylactic move which
has not been played much. We keep all our options open and are ready to meet
the move e4.} 12. e4 (12. e3 {does not make much sense now.} e5 13. d5 c6 $11)
12... c5 $1 {The point of Re8 was to ensure that white is not able to meet c5
with d5 closing down the center. We want to try and blast open the central
files with the king on e1.} (12... e5 13. d5 $14) 13. Bd3 d5 $1 {We should
always try to make this move work. Here we make use of the bishop on h4.} 14.
e5 Ne4 15. Bxd8 Nxc3 {This sequence with Ne4 was always a possibility but
forcing the pawn to e5 makes it a much better version for us.} 16. Bh4 (16.
bxc3 Raxd8 $11) (16. Bxb6 Nxb6 17. bxc3 cxd4 18. c5 dxc3 $11 {black it at
least equal in the resulting endgame.}) 16... cxd4 $1 {We sacrifice a piece
for the central pawns!} (16... Na4 {is also an interesting option.} 17. cxd5
cxd4 18. Bb5 Nac5 19. b4 Ba6 20. Bc6 Nd3+ 21. Kd1 N7xe5 {Here also we win the
central pawns but for an exchange.} 22. Bxa8 Rxa8 $44) 17. bxc3 dxc3 18. Nb3
Nxe5 19. Be2 dxc4 20. Nc1 Nc6 $1 {The knight is heading to its ideal square on
d4.} 21. Bxc4 (21. Bd1 e5 22. Ne2 c2 23. Bxc2 Nd4 $44 {We will continue with g5
and Rad8.}) 21... Nd4 22. O-O {We need to go for a forcing line here.} Nc2 23.
Ra2 Ne3 24. Bb5 Nxf1 25. Bxe8 Bd5 $1 {We gain a tempo against the rook.} 26.
Ra1 Rxe8 27. Kxf1 c2 $44 {The pawn on c2 gives us enough compensation for the
piece. We do have three pawns for the knight.} *

