{[%evp 0,48,25,19,21,4,4,4,28,-6,0,0,11,19,-2,-2,7,-15,-12,-12,3,-1,14,13,13,
13,13,9,2,2,73,2,5,2,-31,-31,5,-12,46,48,30,24,24,20,23,18,37,37,29,29,29] How
to continue here?} 17... e5 $1 {We just want to blast open the position. The
white king will want to castle queenside and we want to get our bishop to g4
before that.} 18. O-O-O (18. Nf5 Qxg4 $19) (18. Bxe5 Re8 $1 19. O-O-O Bxc3 {
Now white is the one who has to be very careful.} 20. Bxg7 (20. bxc3 Bxg4 21.
Rdg1 Rxe5 22. exd5 f5 $1 $11) (20. exd5 $6 Bxg4 $1 {a nice intermediate move.}
21. Qxg6 (21. Rdg1 Bxd4 22. Bxd4 Re4 $19) 21... hxg6 $15) 20... Bxg4 21. Qxc3
Rxe4 22. Rhg1 Qxg7 23. Nf5 Qxc3+ 24. bxc3 Kf8 $11) 18... Bxc3 19. Nf5 $1 {
The line is pretty crazy but we should be able to remember it if we understand
the logic behind the moves. white is threatening to go Ne7 or open up the 'g'
file for the rook.} Bxf5 20. gxf5 Qa6 21. Qxc3 (21. bxc3 exf4 22. cxd5 Qd6 {
The position is pretty complex still but we should be doing well if we can get
a blockade in the center.} 23. Rh3 Rac8 24. Rf3 Rc4 $36) 21... d4 $1 22. Qd2 (
22. Qb3 exf4 23. Rxd4 Rac8 24. Kb1 Rfd8 25. Rhd1 Rxd4 26. Rxd4 Qc6 $11) 22...
Qxc4+ 23. Kb1 exf4 24. f6 Qc6 25. Qxf4 Qxf6 $11 {Should lead to a draw here.} *

